04310nam a22005535i 9780822393245DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223932457 a10.1515/97808223932452doi  a(DE-B1597)553494  a(OCoLC)645326492  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aRM301.27b.A22 2010 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a615/.192221 aAbadie, Roberto, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Professional Guinea Pig :bBig Pharma and the Risky World of Human Subjects /cRoberto Abadie. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (197 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tA NOTE ON METHOD -- tIntroduction. A GUINEA PIG'S WAGE -- t1. GUINEA-PIGGING -- t2. MARKET RECRUITMENT, IDENTITY, AND RESISTANCE AMONG PROFESSIONAL GUINEA PIGS -- t3. LOCAL KNOWLEDGE AND RISK MANAGEMENT AMONG PROFESSIONAL GUINEA PIGS -- t4. BIG PHARMA AND HIV CLINICAL TRIALS -- t5. STRATEGIES OF SURVIVAL -- t6. FROM PRISONERS TO PROFESSIONALS -- t7. ETHICS AND THE EXPLOITATION OF THE POOR IN CLINICAL TRIALS RESEARCH -- tConclusion. LIVING IN/OFF THE MILD TORTURE ECONOMY AS TRIAL SUBJECTS -- tEpilogue. FOLLOWING UP -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Professional Guinea Pig documents the emergence of the professional research subject in Phase I clinical trials testing the safety of drugs in development. Until the mid-1970s Phase I trials were conducted on prisoners. After that practice was outlawed, the pharmaceutical industry needed a replacement population and began to aggressively recruit healthy, paid subjects, some of whom came to depend on the income, earning their living by continuously taking part in these trials. Drawing on ethnographic research among self-identified "professional guinea pigs" in Philadelphia, Roberto Abadie examines their experiences and views on the conduct of the trials and the risks they assume by participating. Some of the research subjects he met had taken part in more than eighty Phase I trials. While the professional guinea pigs tended to believe that most clinical trials pose only a moderate health risk, Abadie contends that the hazards presented by continuous participation, such as exposure to potentially dangerous drug interactions, are discounted or ignored by research subjects in need of money. The risks to professional guinea pigs are also disregarded by the pharmaceutical industry, which has become dependent on the routine participation of experienced research subjects. Arguing that financial incentives compromise the ethical imperative for informed consent to be freely given by clinical-trials subjects, Abadie confirms the need to reform policies regulating the participation of paid subjects in Phase I clinical trials.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aDrugsxTesting. 0aDrugszUnited StatesxTesting. 0aHuman experimentation in medicinezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393245zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393245423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393245.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles